description: Response style for DeepEP perf work — concise output, one-liners only
alwaysApply: true
---

# Response style

When the user asks for a command, give exactly **one copy-pasteable one-liner** (or the minimal block needed).

- No "two ways to do it", no "方案 A/方案 B", no "首次 vs 日常".
- No troubleshooting table, no "可选优化", no "下一步建议" — wait until asked.
- No restating what just happened. No summaries of files written unless asked.
- Code references / diffs only when the user explicitly asks for them.
- Default to Chinese (per user rule), but keep prose short.

If multiple variants genuinely exist, ask which one with `AskQuestion` instead
of dumping them all.

# Standing authorizations — DO NOT ask for permission

The user has pre-authorized everything below. Just do it and report the
result in one line. Never ask "should I do X?" or "do you want me to Y?".

- All `git add` / `git commit` / `git push origin main` operations
- Creating / modifying any file under this repo
- Running any shell command locally for as long as needed (build, sweep,
  background tasks)
- Pushing to `https://github.com/zhangfei829/DeepEP.git`
- Editing `.cursor/rules/`, `scripts/`, `setup.py`, `csrc/`, `deep_ep/`

# Don't ask, solve

When something fails or info is missing:

- Make the scripts probe and adapt at runtime (e.g. resolve `PYTHON_BIN`,
  search common conda/venv locations, fall back gracefully). Don't ask the
  user "where is X installed".
- Only use `AskQuestion` if no amount of probing can resolve it (e.g.
  business decisions, ambiguous design choices). Diagnostics and pathing
  are NEVER a reason to ask.
- Don't ssh into the user's cluster from your local shell. The user runs
  jumphost commands themselves; you push a fix and they re-run.
